WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.956 --> 00:00:04.302
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:06.255 --> 00:00:08.130
BONITA STEWART: How many
of you have actually

00:00:08.130 --> 00:00:11.310
heard of "The Third
Metric," so we can-- OK.

00:00:11.310 --> 00:00:11.820
Great.

00:00:11.820 --> 00:00:13.280
But some of you have not.

00:00:13.280 --> 00:00:15.160
And so part of
"The Third Metric"

00:00:15.160 --> 00:00:19.820
is moving just beyond
money and power.

00:00:19.820 --> 00:00:23.490
So I thought, Arianna,
could you talk to us

00:00:23.490 --> 00:00:26.520
a little bit about what does
it mean, what does success

00:00:26.520 --> 00:00:30.350
look like when you start to
think about a third metric

00:00:30.350 --> 00:00:31.707
and what it means?

00:00:31.707 --> 00:00:33.290
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON:
Well first of all,

00:00:33.290 --> 00:00:35.360
I'm delighted to be
here, and delighted

00:00:35.360 --> 00:00:37.860
to have this conversation
with you, Bonita.

00:00:37.860 --> 00:00:41.060
And I loved our
last panel and what

00:00:41.060 --> 00:00:43.110
you said, that I'm
going to query you

00:00:43.110 --> 00:00:45.220
on about sacred spaces.

00:00:45.220 --> 00:00:47.350
And so the third
metric is an idea

00:00:47.350 --> 00:00:51.540
that occurred to me after I
collapsed from exhaustion,

00:00:51.540 --> 00:00:56.310
burnout, and sleep deprivation,
which is how I start the book.

00:00:56.310 --> 00:01:00.610
And as I came to-- that
was seven years ago--

00:01:00.610 --> 00:01:04.379
in a pool of blood,
having broken my cheekbone

00:01:04.379 --> 00:01:08.242
and got four stitches
on top of my right eye,

00:01:08.242 --> 00:01:11.940
I basically started asking
a lot of these questions

00:01:11.940 --> 00:01:16.060
that we often stop asking
when we leave college,

00:01:16.060 --> 00:01:17.370
like what is a good life?

00:01:17.370 --> 00:01:18.950
What is success?

00:01:18.950 --> 00:01:23.770
And why by conventional
definitions of success

00:01:23.770 --> 00:01:25.240
are successful.

00:01:25.240 --> 00:01:27.390
By any sane
definition of success,

00:01:27.390 --> 00:01:30.170
if you come to in a pool of
blood and nobody has shot you,

00:01:30.170 --> 00:01:33.330
you're not successful.

00:01:33.330 --> 00:01:36.920
So that's when I started
thinking our society

00:01:36.920 --> 00:01:38.850
defines success in
terms of these two

00:01:38.850 --> 00:01:40.620
metrics of money and power.

00:01:40.620 --> 00:01:42.700
We give them different
names, but that's

00:01:42.700 --> 00:01:44.510
what it comes down to.

00:01:44.510 --> 00:01:48.850
And I came to the conclusion
that life is really not

00:01:48.850 --> 00:01:51.130
complete without
the third metric.

00:01:51.130 --> 00:01:53.580
It's really like the
third leg of the stool.

00:01:53.580 --> 00:01:55.850
The first two metrics
are the two legs.

00:01:55.850 --> 00:01:59.420
And you basically try
to sit on the stool,

00:01:59.420 --> 00:02:02.620
and you will at
some point fall off,

00:02:02.620 --> 00:02:04.890
because it's not sustainable.

00:02:04.890 --> 00:02:07.320
The third metric consists
of these four pillars,

00:02:07.320 --> 00:02:10.330
and each of the pillars
is a section in the book.

00:02:10.330 --> 00:02:14.710
Well being, which
starts with sleep.

00:02:14.710 --> 00:02:17.230
Because I love the fact
that Googlers are all

00:02:17.230 --> 00:02:19.500
about data and evidence, right?

00:02:19.500 --> 00:02:24.640
That's why I have in the book 55
pages of scientific end notes.

00:02:24.640 --> 00:02:28.600
Because all the things about
sleep, meditation, renewal

00:02:28.600 --> 00:02:36.120
pauses are not kind of new
agey, flaky, California stuff.

00:02:36.120 --> 00:02:38.780
They are actually
scientifically-based

00:02:38.780 --> 00:02:41.220
performance enhancement tools.

00:02:41.220 --> 00:02:43.690
And for all the
skeptics in the room,

00:02:43.690 --> 00:02:45.790
look at the scientific data.

00:02:45.790 --> 00:02:48.140
All the major universities
now, for example,

00:02:48.140 --> 00:02:51.510
have a sleep division as part
of their medicine school.

00:02:51.510 --> 00:02:54.040
In fact, I became such
a sleep evangelist

00:02:54.040 --> 00:02:57.110
that Harvard asked me to join
the board of their school

00:02:57.110 --> 00:02:59.290
of medicine sleep division.

00:02:59.290 --> 00:03:04.810
That gives you an idea of
how much I talk about it.

00:03:04.810 --> 00:03:06.890
In fact, I gave a
commencement at Smith,

00:03:06.890 --> 00:03:10.150
and I told the women graduates
to sleep their way to the top.

00:03:17.020 --> 00:03:19.790
And I was a late
convert, because I

00:03:19.790 --> 00:03:22.890
came to this realization
having collapsed

00:03:22.890 --> 00:03:25.790
after I used to get
four to five hours.

00:03:25.790 --> 00:03:27.670
And then I read
the scientific data

00:03:27.670 --> 00:03:30.170
and realized that if I
got seven to eight hours,

00:03:30.170 --> 00:03:32.890
I would actually be more
productive, more creative, less

00:03:32.890 --> 00:03:35.150
reactive, and happier.

00:03:35.150 --> 00:03:37.780
So it became a priority.

00:03:37.780 --> 00:03:40.950
And just very quickly, the
second pillar is wisdom.

00:03:40.950 --> 00:03:42.930
And we can talk more about that.

00:03:42.930 --> 00:03:45.320
But everybody here
wants to be creative.

00:03:45.320 --> 00:03:47.430
And every creative
person will tell you

00:03:47.430 --> 00:03:51.970
that creativity is not the
product of clearing our email

00:03:51.970 --> 00:03:55.230
box, or being on
the zone, it's often

00:03:55.230 --> 00:03:57.500
the product of
these Eureka moments

00:03:57.500 --> 00:04:00.780
which come when we create
some space in our lives

00:04:00.780 --> 00:04:03.360
in which to hear
the whisperings,

00:04:03.360 --> 00:04:07.000
as Steve Jobs called it,
and basically connect

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:10.950
with some deeper wisdom
and deeper insights.

00:04:10.950 --> 00:04:13.990
The third part of the
third metric is wonder.

00:04:13.990 --> 00:04:17.130
Being connected with the
wonder, the mystery of life.

00:04:17.130 --> 00:04:20.649
Often just the ordinary
beauty of life.

00:04:20.649 --> 00:04:23.070
We spend so much
time multitasking.

00:04:23.070 --> 00:04:25.500
I mean, you walk down
the streets of New York,

00:04:25.500 --> 00:04:28.450
and hardly anybody's
just walking.

00:04:28.450 --> 00:04:31.730
People are either walking
and being on the phone,

00:04:31.730 --> 00:04:35.610
walking and texting, and also
if they're walking and texting,

00:04:35.610 --> 00:04:38.020
the assumption seems to
be that if you are not

00:04:38.020 --> 00:04:40.880
texting while walking, it means
you're not as busy and not as

00:04:40.880 --> 00:04:44.500
important, so you better
get out of the way.

00:04:44.500 --> 00:04:49.350
And I remember when I stopped
doing that seven years ago, I

00:04:49.350 --> 00:04:53.400
started noticing things that
I had completely ignored,

00:04:53.400 --> 00:04:56.360
like this beautiful
building by my apartment.

00:04:56.360 --> 00:04:58.870
And I remember I told a
friend, "This is so beautiful.

00:04:58.870 --> 00:05:00.420
Look at the
ornamentation at the top.

00:05:00.420 --> 00:05:01.350
When did it go up?"

00:05:01.350 --> 00:05:05.520
And she said, "1890."

00:05:05.520 --> 00:05:07.070
So what else are we missing?

00:05:07.070 --> 00:05:09.420
And the final pillar is giving.

00:05:09.420 --> 00:05:14.660
That giving is really part of
a completely fulfilled life.

00:05:14.660 --> 00:05:19.000
And it starts with small acts
of connecting with people

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:23.000
that otherwise you might take
for granted in our daily lives.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:25.300
BONITA STEWART: So in
the book you talk about,

00:05:25.300 --> 00:05:33.200
this is not a simple
thing to actually thrive.

00:05:33.200 --> 00:05:35.290
You have to know
what you're doing.

00:05:35.290 --> 00:05:37.950
You have to think about
it and be more conscious.

00:05:37.950 --> 00:05:42.280
And I think for the women-- and
there's even a question here--

00:05:42.280 --> 00:05:47.360
but we've all been told now
with this worldwide conversation

00:05:47.360 --> 00:05:52.910
on leaning in, how do
we go about leaning in.

00:05:52.910 --> 00:05:56.480
And then also this
notion of having

00:05:56.480 --> 00:06:01.830
a life where you can thrive, and
just invoke this third metric.

00:06:01.830 --> 00:06:07.167
How would you address the women
in terms of those two aspects?

00:06:07.167 --> 00:06:08.750
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON:
Well first of all,

00:06:08.750 --> 00:06:11.150
I think these two are
completely compatible,

00:06:11.150 --> 00:06:14.630
which is why Sheryl Sandberg did
a big endorsement of the book,

00:06:14.630 --> 00:06:16.550
and actually did the
first conversation.

00:06:16.550 --> 00:06:18.920
I've had a series
of conversations

00:06:18.920 --> 00:06:21.270
with women like you, which
has been really great.

00:06:21.270 --> 00:06:23.980
And Sheryl Sandberg
did the first one

00:06:23.980 --> 00:06:27.010
when the book came out at the
end of March in San Francisco,

00:06:27.010 --> 00:06:28.570
at the Symphony Hall.

00:06:28.570 --> 00:06:31.140
And the reason for that
is to make it clear

00:06:31.140 --> 00:06:37.470
that thriving and taking care
of the third metric in our lives

00:06:37.470 --> 00:06:40.200
doesn't mean that we
don't have big dreams,

00:06:40.200 --> 00:06:42.430
or accomplish big things.

00:06:42.430 --> 00:06:45.600
It just means
recognizing that we're

00:06:45.600 --> 00:06:48.740
going to lean in more
effectively if we learn

00:06:48.740 --> 00:06:55.020
to lean back, recharge
ourselves, and lean in.

00:06:55.020 --> 00:06:57.220
It's like a dance.

00:06:57.220 --> 00:07:01.995
And if anybody here has a
cat, if you look at cats,

00:07:01.995 --> 00:07:03.030
you know what they do.

00:07:03.030 --> 00:07:05.220
They kind of-- if
they're going to jump,

00:07:05.220 --> 00:07:07.910
they lean back before they jump.

00:07:07.910 --> 00:07:10.185
In French, for those
who speak French,

00:07:10.185 --> 00:07:11.870
there is a term
called reculer pour

00:07:11.870 --> 00:07:13.880
mieux sauter, which
literally means,

00:07:13.880 --> 00:07:16.790
lean back in order
to jump higher.

00:07:16.790 --> 00:07:20.730
And it's really what modern
science has demonstrated,

00:07:20.730 --> 00:07:25.790
which is the need for recovery
time, they need for renewal.

00:07:25.790 --> 00:07:28.770
And really, ahead of
women and businesspeople,

00:07:28.770 --> 00:07:32.320
athletes having incorporated
these practices.

00:07:32.320 --> 00:07:35.460
I was in Los Angeles and
I met with Kobe Bryant

00:07:35.460 --> 00:07:36.590
a couple of weeks ago.

00:07:36.590 --> 00:07:39.480
And he was telling me how
he has a nap-- sometimes

00:07:39.480 --> 00:07:44.500
a 90 minute nap before
he gets out to play.

00:07:44.500 --> 00:07:48.110
And that clears his
mind, de-stresses him,

00:07:48.110 --> 00:07:50.680
and allows him to
be fully present.

00:07:50.680 --> 00:07:53.790
Now when he said Phil
Jackson, their coach,

00:07:53.790 --> 00:07:58.740
started having them meditate
and do Tai Chi, and have naps,

00:07:58.740 --> 00:08:00.870
they all kind of looked
at the him aghast.

00:08:00.870 --> 00:08:04.580
But he was like this amazing
coach, so they all did it.

00:08:04.580 --> 00:08:09.050
And then they began to see
the impact it had on them.

00:08:09.050 --> 00:08:11.130
So that's really why
there's absolutely

00:08:11.130 --> 00:08:14.470
no contradiction
between the two.

00:08:14.470 --> 00:08:17.500
If we just lean in without
leaning back and recharging,

00:08:17.500 --> 00:08:19.120
that's when we fall over.

00:08:19.120 --> 00:08:23.020
And you see so many women-- not
just my own experience-- look

00:08:23.020 --> 00:08:25.030
at what happened
to Hilary Clinton.

00:08:25.030 --> 00:08:29.220
She literally collapsed, again
from exhaustion and burnout.

00:08:29.220 --> 00:08:31.140
And hers was more
serious-- ended up

00:08:31.140 --> 00:08:33.480
with a clot in the brain.

00:08:33.480 --> 00:08:37.620
And you look around
and you see men

00:08:37.620 --> 00:08:41.350
having heart attacks in their
'50s, high blood pressure,

00:08:41.350 --> 00:08:46.380
and diabetes, pulmonary
embolisms-- all of these

00:08:46.380 --> 00:08:48.780
are stress-related diseases.

00:08:48.780 --> 00:08:51.630
And 3/4 of our
health care costs now

00:08:51.630 --> 00:08:54.900
are because of stress-related
chronic preventable diseases.

00:08:54.900 --> 00:08:58.100
So basically, what I'm saying
when it comes to women,

00:08:58.100 --> 00:09:04.000
is women should not just want
to be at the top of the world.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.310
They also want to
change the world.

00:09:06.310 --> 00:09:10.380
Because the way it's been
working is not sustainable.

00:09:10.380 --> 00:09:12.540
BONITA STEWART: So
it's interesting.

00:09:12.540 --> 00:09:15.572
I started tracking, just
learning more about the sleep.

00:09:15.572 --> 00:09:17.030
And my husband
said, "I don't think

00:09:17.030 --> 00:09:18.610
you're getting enough sleep."

00:09:18.610 --> 00:09:19.330
And I said, "Aw."

00:09:19.330 --> 00:09:20.940
But then you look at the data.

00:09:20.940 --> 00:09:24.680
And then the data tells
you in fact, you're not.

00:09:24.680 --> 00:09:29.590
But when you do, it just adds
so much to your well being.

00:09:29.590 --> 00:09:31.370
One of the things
Arianna, that you

00:09:31.370 --> 00:09:34.660
talked about in the book, which
I think just made me smile,

00:09:34.660 --> 00:09:38.000
because I think we all can
hearken back to our childhood,

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:41.360
and when we did have
that sense of wonder.

00:09:41.360 --> 00:09:46.360
Can you just elaborate on
wonder and how we can actually

00:09:46.360 --> 00:09:49.800
bring that back into our lives.

00:09:49.800 --> 00:09:53.682
Because I thought that was an
interesting aspect of the book.

00:09:53.682 --> 00:09:55.140
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON:
Well thank you.

00:09:55.140 --> 00:09:58.970
Because I actually love
that chapter particularly,

00:09:58.970 --> 00:10:04.510
because everybody here--
let's just take everybody

00:10:04.510 --> 00:10:06.720
in the room-- is really curious.

00:10:06.720 --> 00:10:07.220
Right?

00:10:07.220 --> 00:10:08.860
You wouldn't be here
if you were not.

00:10:08.860 --> 00:10:12.560
You are curious about
everything, from whatever you

00:10:12.560 --> 00:10:15.480
can Google, and any
amount of big data,

00:10:15.480 --> 00:10:20.430
to finding out
about Mars or Venus.

00:10:20.430 --> 00:10:24.670
But we're not really
particularly curious

00:10:24.670 --> 00:10:28.420
how about our inner
space, our inner space

00:10:28.420 --> 00:10:29.805
exploration of who are we?

00:10:29.805 --> 00:10:31.580
Why are we here?

00:10:31.580 --> 00:10:32.995
And why do we die?

00:10:32.995 --> 00:10:35.000
You know, all these
questions, I find

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:37.270
them completely fascinating.

00:10:37.270 --> 00:10:42.050
And I have a lot of friends
who find them fascinating.

00:10:42.050 --> 00:10:44.670
So we have a lot of
these conversations.

00:10:44.670 --> 00:10:49.680
And if you think of it as
The Onion headline put it--

00:10:49.680 --> 00:10:51.645
death rate holds steady at 100%.

00:10:54.620 --> 00:10:58.300
So much though we want to
ignore it, it's a reality.

00:10:58.300 --> 00:11:04.150
And when somebody dies
who is close to us,

00:11:04.150 --> 00:11:06.230
it makes us often
look at our lives

00:11:06.230 --> 00:11:08.140
and really kind of recalibrate.

00:11:08.140 --> 00:11:11.860
I was meeting with Jared Cohen
upstairs before I came down.

00:11:11.860 --> 00:11:13.370
And we were talking about that.

00:11:13.370 --> 00:11:17.070
And he told me when Michael
Hastings died suddenly

00:11:17.070 --> 00:11:21.560
in a car crash, and was his
age-- 31 I think when he died.

00:11:21.560 --> 00:11:23.610
Jared is 32 now.

00:11:23.610 --> 00:11:28.160
He said it made him just
recalibrate his own life.

00:11:28.160 --> 00:11:31.970
It made him prioritize
friendships, for example.

00:11:31.970 --> 00:11:35.090
And whatever impact it
has on each one of us.

00:11:35.090 --> 00:11:36.700
So I think these
are conversations

00:11:36.700 --> 00:11:41.490
which make us reintegrate the
sense of wonder and mystery

00:11:41.490 --> 00:11:42.100
about life.

00:11:42.100 --> 00:11:44.910
Wherever we are in the spectrum
of religion and spiritually

00:11:44.910 --> 00:11:45.600
doesn't matter.

00:11:45.600 --> 00:11:48.350
I have friends of mine
who are religious,

00:11:48.350 --> 00:11:51.290
and friends of mine who
are complete atheists.

00:11:51.290 --> 00:11:55.480
As Reid Hoffman calls
himself-- a mystical atheist.

00:11:55.480 --> 00:11:57.210
He says, "I'm an
atheist, but I'm

00:11:57.210 --> 00:11:59.950
very aware of the
mystery of life.

00:11:59.950 --> 00:12:02.410
I'm very aware that there's
a lot I don't understand.

00:12:02.410 --> 00:12:04.940
And I like the exploration."

00:12:04.940 --> 00:12:07.260
So I like the exploration.

00:12:07.260 --> 00:12:10.070
And I like the
conversation around it,

00:12:10.070 --> 00:12:15.850
because I feel it enriches life
and opens up our perception

00:12:15.850 --> 00:12:18.340
to things that
otherwise we would miss.

00:12:18.340 --> 00:12:22.700
That's why I have a section in
that chapter on coincidences,

00:12:22.700 --> 00:12:25.500
because a lot of
people-- even people are

00:12:25.500 --> 00:12:28.100
complete atheists who don't
think there's anything

00:12:28.100 --> 00:12:32.100
to life beyond what we see and
touch and feel and smell-- they

00:12:32.100 --> 00:12:36.700
love coincidences because it
sort of makes us stop and feel,

00:12:36.700 --> 00:12:38.510
is there some kind
of hidden purpose

00:12:38.510 --> 00:12:39.920
to what's happening
in our lives?

00:12:39.920 --> 00:12:42.720
Because this coincidence
is absolutely amazing.

00:12:42.720 --> 00:12:45.040
And some of them are
trivial coincidences,

00:12:45.040 --> 00:12:47.930
I have some of them in the
book too, and some of them

00:12:47.930 --> 00:12:49.590
are significant coincidences.

00:12:49.590 --> 00:12:54.350
But I remember I mention a
trivial coincidence, when there

00:12:54.350 --> 00:12:57.200
was somebody taking
a survey at a mall

00:12:57.200 --> 00:13:02.910
and asks people to give
them their numbers.

00:13:02.910 --> 00:13:09.840
And one person gave him a
number that he made up--

00:13:09.840 --> 00:13:11.220
the phone number.

00:13:11.220 --> 00:13:13.970
And the server said,
"That's not your number."

00:13:13.970 --> 00:13:16.010
And the guy said, "Why
isn't it my number?"

00:13:16.010 --> 00:13:20.740
He said, "Because
that's my number."

00:13:20.740 --> 00:13:23.070
And so it suddenly stops you.

00:13:23.070 --> 00:13:25.200
I doesn't mean anything,
but it stops you,

00:13:25.200 --> 00:13:29.360
because what is the
probability of this happening?

00:13:29.360 --> 00:13:33.830
So when things happen that have
an incredibly astronomically

00:13:33.830 --> 00:13:36.120
high probability
of them happening,

00:13:36.120 --> 00:13:41.140
it stops us and makes
us just look at life,

00:13:41.140 --> 00:13:43.740
and look at the possibility
that maybe there

00:13:43.740 --> 00:13:47.190
is some kind of hidden
purpose and maybe even

00:13:47.190 --> 00:13:51.550
somebody with a sense
of humor behind it.

00:13:51.550 --> 00:13:53.550
BONITA STEWART: So why
don't we start lining up,

00:13:53.550 --> 00:13:56.900
because I know many of you
have questions in the room.

00:13:56.900 --> 00:13:58.930
And I'm going to go
through the Dory questions.

00:13:58.930 --> 00:14:00.554
But start thinking
about your questions

00:14:00.554 --> 00:14:01.590
and line up at the mics.

00:14:01.590 --> 00:14:02.510
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON: And
while we're doing that,

00:14:02.510 --> 00:14:03.700
can I ask you a question?

00:14:03.700 --> 00:14:04.160
BONITA STEWART: Sure.

00:14:04.160 --> 00:14:04.660
Of course.

00:14:04.660 --> 00:14:08.320
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON: Because
we did an interview with you

00:14:08.320 --> 00:14:09.500
for The Huffington Post.

00:14:09.500 --> 00:14:11.360
And you had something
very interesting.

00:14:11.360 --> 00:14:13.630
I don't know if
everybody here knows

00:14:13.630 --> 00:14:16.050
that Bonita is a ballet dancer.

00:14:16.050 --> 00:14:20.840
And when you were in
ballet practice one day--

00:14:20.840 --> 00:14:23.450
you said normally you don't
bring your smartphone in,

00:14:23.450 --> 00:14:25.260
this is your sacred time.

00:14:25.260 --> 00:14:30.040
But one day you just
looked at your smartphone,

00:14:30.040 --> 00:14:32.940
and the minute you looked
at your smartphone,

00:14:32.940 --> 00:14:37.250
your whole work life included
into that sacred space.

00:14:37.250 --> 00:14:39.650
And the rest of the time
you could not be as present.

00:14:39.650 --> 00:14:42.820
And I think that's just
a great example of why

00:14:42.820 --> 00:14:46.970
it's important for us
to create those spaces

00:14:46.970 --> 00:14:49.960
where we disconnect
from our technology

00:14:49.960 --> 00:14:52.950
and reconnect with
ourselves or our loved ones,

00:14:52.950 --> 00:14:54.590
or the present moment.

00:14:54.590 --> 00:14:56.176
And I just loved the story.

00:14:56.176 --> 00:14:57.800
You can tell us a
little more about it.

00:14:57.800 --> 00:15:00.420
BONITA STEWART: Yeah,
so I've shared this.

00:15:00.420 --> 00:15:03.240
But I do take ballet class.

00:15:03.240 --> 00:15:06.980
And I just decided
during the break--

00:15:06.980 --> 00:15:09.615
once you leave, you do the
floor, and then you leave.

00:15:09.615 --> 00:15:11.240
And you take a break
and you come back,

00:15:11.240 --> 00:15:14.010
and you do the combination.

00:15:14.010 --> 00:15:17.770
And so I looked at my phone,
and I had received a call,

00:15:17.770 --> 00:15:23.590
and it just changed everything
about the rest of the class.

00:15:23.590 --> 00:15:25.990
I couldn't do my pirouette.

00:15:25.990 --> 00:15:28.270
I wasn't focusing
on the combination.

00:15:28.270 --> 00:15:30.170
I just decided at
that point this

00:15:30.170 --> 00:15:32.700
is the one thing that
is so important to me--

00:15:32.700 --> 00:15:34.790
this is my sacred space.

00:15:34.790 --> 00:15:40.500
And I'm not going to let
technology invade my space when

00:15:40.500 --> 00:15:42.140
I'm taking ballet.

00:15:42.140 --> 00:15:44.540
So I just, I made
that as a point.

00:15:44.540 --> 00:15:47.950
And I do think that all of us
have to-- especially when we're

00:15:47.950 --> 00:15:50.780
24/7 in many cases
with technology--

00:15:50.780 --> 00:15:54.080
we do have to be very
conscious about making sure

00:15:54.080 --> 00:15:56.700
that we do have a sacred space.

00:15:56.700 --> 00:15:58.937
So what is yours, Arianna?

00:15:58.937 --> 00:16:00.520
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON:
So my sacred space

00:16:00.520 --> 00:16:03.869
is first of all, at night--
and this is one of the 12 steps

00:16:03.869 --> 00:16:04.660
I have in the book.

00:16:04.660 --> 00:16:07.180
I have 12 steps that I
recommend for people.

00:16:07.180 --> 00:16:09.230
And I picked 12
deliberately because we

00:16:09.230 --> 00:16:13.910
are addicted to this current
way of being perpetually on,

00:16:13.910 --> 00:16:17.700
and even addicted to burnout.

00:16:17.700 --> 00:16:21.727
So the first step for
me is picking a time

00:16:21.727 --> 00:16:25.570
at the end of my day when
I turn off all my devices

00:16:25.570 --> 00:16:27.870
and gently escort them
out of my bedroom.

00:16:31.990 --> 00:16:36.190
Because if I keep my iPhone,
say, charging by my bed,

00:16:36.190 --> 00:16:38.760
and I wake up in the middle of
the night for whatever reason,

00:16:38.760 --> 00:16:42.470
I'm going to be tempted
to look at my data.

00:16:42.470 --> 00:16:45.740
And I don't want my day life
to intrude into my night life.

00:16:45.740 --> 00:16:47.650
I want to wake up fully charged.

00:16:47.650 --> 00:16:50.941
Because again, the science shows
that if you look at your data

00:16:50.941 --> 00:16:52.440
in the middle of
the night, A-- it's

00:16:52.440 --> 00:16:55.420
going to take you longer
to go back to sleep.

00:16:55.420 --> 00:16:57.910
And when you go back to sleep,
it's not going to be as deep

00:16:57.910 --> 00:17:02.250
and recharging, because your
brain has started already

00:17:02.250 --> 00:17:06.385
processing things you
have to do during the day.

00:17:06.385 --> 00:17:08.510
BONITA STEWART: So let's
take some of the questions

00:17:08.510 --> 00:17:09.369
from the Dory.

00:17:09.369 --> 00:17:12.849
So one question we
actually covered,

00:17:12.849 --> 00:17:15.339
just Cheryl's book
in terms of lean in,

00:17:15.339 --> 00:17:17.569
but what kind of
meditation do you practice?

00:17:17.569 --> 00:17:19.910
And you have a specific
mantra or mantras

00:17:19.910 --> 00:17:23.660
that you come back to
in times of high stress?

00:17:23.660 --> 00:17:26.640
So what do you do in
those high stress times?

00:17:26.640 --> 00:17:29.630
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON: So
I now meditate every day

00:17:29.630 --> 00:17:33.740
in the morning for about 20
minutes, sometimes longer If I

00:17:33.740 --> 00:17:34.490
can.

00:17:34.490 --> 00:17:38.340
But in the book I recommend that
you start with five minutes,

00:17:38.340 --> 00:17:40.880
because everybody
has five minutes.

00:17:40.880 --> 00:17:42.510
And to remember
one thing-- there

00:17:42.510 --> 00:17:45.680
is no wrong way to meditate.

00:17:45.680 --> 00:17:48.550
Because everybody here
is a perfectionist.

00:17:48.550 --> 00:17:52.090
You want to do everything right.

00:17:52.090 --> 00:17:54.230
So that's where you
have to surrender.

00:17:54.230 --> 00:17:57.350
All you have to do is
give yourself five minutes

00:17:57.350 --> 00:17:59.920
and concentrate on your breath.

00:17:59.920 --> 00:18:02.070
I have specific
steps in the book,

00:18:02.070 --> 00:18:05.310
but you don't even have
to worry about a mantra.

00:18:05.310 --> 00:18:08.580
You can just focus on the
inhalation and exhalation

00:18:08.580 --> 00:18:12.650
I also have an appendix
with 12 meditation apps.

00:18:12.650 --> 00:18:15.810
I know it's a paradox
to use technology

00:18:15.810 --> 00:18:17.870
to help us disconnect
from technology,

00:18:17.870 --> 00:18:20.015
but hey, whatever it takes.

00:18:20.015 --> 00:18:24.100
So I have picked my 12
favorite meditation apps,

00:18:24.100 --> 00:18:27.510
if you want to be walked
through a meditation.

00:18:27.510 --> 00:18:29.540
One of my favorites
is Headspace.

00:18:29.540 --> 00:18:31.620
Is anybody here on Headspace?

00:18:31.620 --> 00:18:36.620
It's a really great app that
was created by an Englishman who

00:18:36.620 --> 00:18:39.520
then became a Buddhist monk,
and then became a juggler.

00:18:43.190 --> 00:18:44.610
And it's really great.

00:18:44.610 --> 00:18:50.430
And now you know, it's really
become very popular in England.

00:18:50.430 --> 00:18:52.110
Even the Bank of
England is using

00:18:52.110 --> 00:18:55.780
it, which is part of the
amazing thing that has happened.

00:18:55.780 --> 00:19:01.300
In 2013, meditation
became mainstream.

00:19:01.300 --> 00:19:04.910
And CEO's started coming out
not as being gay, but as being

00:19:04.910 --> 00:19:06.480
meditators.

00:19:06.480 --> 00:19:10.160
Like Ray Dalio, the co-founder
of one of the biggest hedge

00:19:10.160 --> 00:19:12.580
funds, Bridgewater,
came out saying

00:19:12.580 --> 00:19:15.410
I've been meditating
for 35 years.

00:19:15.410 --> 00:19:17.800
And I consider it the
foundation of my success.

00:19:17.800 --> 00:19:20.790
Mark Benioff, the
CEO of Salesforce.

00:19:20.790 --> 00:19:23.420
Mark Bertolini,
the CEO of Aetna.

00:19:23.420 --> 00:19:24.830
It is really truly amazing.

00:19:24.830 --> 00:19:29.140
In Davos last year
there were 27 sessions

00:19:29.140 --> 00:19:34.060
who CEO's about meditation,
mindfulness, et cetera.

00:19:34.060 --> 00:19:41.290
Just amazing shift in the
zeitgeist around these issues.

00:19:41.290 --> 00:19:42.290
BONITA STEWART: MIchael.

00:19:42.290 --> 00:19:43.630
AUDIENCE: Thanks, Bonita.

