00:20:11.090 --> 00:20:14.210
ad exchange, double click, a
lost of sales type products

00:20:14.210 --> 00:20:14.920
here.

00:20:14.920 --> 00:20:16.110
I started in Mountain View.

00:20:16.110 --> 00:20:18.780
And I came to New York
2 and 1/2 years ago.

00:20:18.780 --> 00:20:21.350
My sacred space.

00:20:21.350 --> 00:20:23.700
I do enjoy a drink
on the weekend.

00:20:23.700 --> 00:20:27.370
So probably any bar.

00:20:27.370 --> 00:20:28.840
But honestly--

00:20:28.840 --> 00:20:31.602
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON:
What's your sacred drink?

00:20:31.602 --> 00:20:33.310
AUDIENCE: I'm into my
whiskies right now.

00:20:33.310 --> 00:20:36.497
But um-- my sacred
space is probably

00:20:36.497 --> 00:20:38.580
either in Tompkins Square
Park, near where I live.

00:20:38.580 --> 00:20:42.210
Or kind of Central Park
with a book of my hand,

00:20:42.210 --> 00:20:43.310
just people watching.

00:20:43.310 --> 00:20:45.350
New York is great for that.

00:20:45.350 --> 00:20:47.730
But my question is,
I think a lot of us

00:20:47.730 --> 00:20:50.530
do seek the conventional
types of success,

00:20:50.530 --> 00:20:53.440
and arguably they
allow you space

00:20:53.440 --> 00:20:55.430
for kind of the third
leg, if you will.

00:20:55.430 --> 00:20:58.170
I'm wondering as you were
building your business,

00:20:58.170 --> 00:21:00.300
looking back, could
you have built it

00:21:00.300 --> 00:21:03.910
to the success it is now with
seven, eight hours of sleep?

00:21:03.910 --> 00:21:05.710
I think there's this
constant hustle we all

00:21:05.710 --> 00:21:09.730
feel, where it's this kind of
need to work harder and more

00:21:09.730 --> 00:21:10.249
often.

00:21:10.249 --> 00:21:12.540
Could you have built the
Huffington Post and you empire

00:21:12.540 --> 00:21:16.180
to what it is now on seven
to eight hours of sleep?

00:21:16.180 --> 00:21:18.500
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON:
Well, great question.

00:21:18.500 --> 00:21:21.080
And I would say
categorically, yes.

00:21:21.080 --> 00:21:24.390
In fact, most of the success
of the Huffington Post

00:21:24.390 --> 00:21:28.820
has been built after my wake up
call, in the last seven years.

00:21:28.820 --> 00:21:29.480
We are nine.

00:21:29.480 --> 00:21:30.850
Years old.

00:21:30.850 --> 00:21:34.210
And I can say
categorically, looking back,

00:21:34.210 --> 00:21:37.590
that the most
important thing you

00:21:37.590 --> 00:21:39.310
can do for a
business, whether it's

00:21:39.310 --> 00:21:43.370
a startup or a big
businesses, is having clarity

00:21:43.370 --> 00:21:45.240
about your vision of
where you're going.

00:21:45.240 --> 00:21:49.030
And for me, it was
very clear for example,

00:21:49.030 --> 00:21:51.720
between the two grow
internationally,

00:21:51.720 --> 00:21:53.640
and this would have
to become a priority,

00:21:53.640 --> 00:21:55.770
and to do it in a way
that would be fast,

00:21:55.770 --> 00:21:58.470
which meant with
partners in each country.

00:21:58.470 --> 00:22:00.760
We are now in 11 countries.

00:22:00.760 --> 00:22:04.410
We're going to be launching
in India and the Middle East

00:22:04.410 --> 00:22:05.022
in the fall.

00:22:05.022 --> 00:22:06.980
And we're also going to
be launching in Greece,

00:22:06.980 --> 00:22:08.270
that I'm very excited about.

00:22:08.270 --> 00:22:10.190
Because I'm Greek, in
case you hadn't noticed.

00:22:10.190 --> 00:22:13.660
This accent is for real.

00:22:13.660 --> 00:22:18.190
And I really believe that having
absolute clarity about where

00:22:18.190 --> 00:22:25.160
you're going is often a function
of operating from a place where

00:22:25.160 --> 00:22:28.490
you are connected to your own
wisdom and a place of insight.

00:22:28.490 --> 00:22:32.120
And I really believe that
about leadership too.

00:22:32.120 --> 00:22:34.110
President Clinton
is quoted in my book

00:22:34.110 --> 00:22:36.710
saying, "The most important
mistakes I made in my life,

00:22:36.710 --> 00:22:38.930
I made when I was tired."

00:22:38.930 --> 00:22:40.540
He did not specify
what mistakes.

00:22:45.100 --> 00:22:48.290
But in our own ways,
we can all say that.

00:22:48.290 --> 00:22:52.980
And everybody who works here,
I mean basically, you're

00:22:52.980 --> 00:22:56.520
not paid for your stamina, you
are paid for your judgment.

00:22:56.520 --> 00:22:58.870
And ultimately you are
paid for your good ideas.

00:22:58.870 --> 00:23:01.240
A good idea is worth everything.

00:23:01.240 --> 00:23:04.330
And the evidence is
overwhelming that you're not

00:23:04.330 --> 00:23:07.190
going to have a lot of good
ideas if you are burnt out.

00:23:07.190 --> 00:23:09.910
You can still operate,
and process things,

00:23:09.910 --> 00:23:12.570
and work through your
email box, et cetera.

00:23:12.570 --> 00:23:15.970
But your function is going to
be more transactional and less

00:23:15.970 --> 00:23:17.080
creative.

00:23:17.080 --> 00:23:20.590
So increasingly now, as we
all have so many machines

00:23:20.590 --> 00:23:24.050
to do a lot of the work
that human beings used

00:23:24.050 --> 00:23:30.650
to do, partly thanks to
Google, we now in fact,

00:23:30.650 --> 00:23:34.920
have an even greater
opportunity to be creative,

00:23:34.920 --> 00:23:36.720
and therefore a
much greater need

00:23:36.720 --> 00:23:40.837
to connect to that place in
us from which we are creative.

00:23:40.837 --> 00:23:41.670
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:23:41.670 --> 00:23:42.920
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON: Thank you.

