You feel you have
to be checking.

00:26:40.650 --> 00:26:43.750
You cannot really be
completely disconnected.

00:26:43.750 --> 00:26:47.000
So we found that
incredibly helpful.

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:51.050
Also, I find that I have
regular walking meetings.

00:26:51.050 --> 00:26:54.130
Instead of having a
meeting in my office,

00:26:54.130 --> 00:26:56.200
I just go for 20
minute, 30 minute

00:26:56.200 --> 00:27:00.730
walk with whoever, one of my
editors or business leaders.

00:27:00.730 --> 00:27:03.360
And we just have our
meeting while walking.

00:27:03.360 --> 00:27:05.900
So I have a pair of
tennis shoes in my office.

00:27:05.900 --> 00:27:08.790
And it's just really great.

00:27:08.790 --> 00:27:14.900
It makes it a completely
concentrated conversation.

00:27:14.900 --> 00:27:17.920
The other thing that
we're just introducing

00:27:17.920 --> 00:27:21.610
is unless you have a
specific reason why

00:27:21.610 --> 00:27:24.835
you need to be on your device,
our meetings are device-free.

00:27:27.350 --> 00:27:30.400
I mean, my leadership
meetings went from one hour

00:27:30.400 --> 00:27:35.720
to half an hour when I said
no devices in the meeting.

00:27:35.720 --> 00:27:37.950
We've given everybody
nice notebooks

00:27:37.950 --> 00:27:40.450
where they can take
notes if they want.

00:27:40.450 --> 00:27:42.140
Does everybody
remember how to write?

00:27:45.700 --> 00:27:50.280
So we are also creating
an well-being committee

00:27:50.280 --> 00:27:52.090
with a lot of
companies, to learn

00:27:52.090 --> 00:27:53.885
from each other in
terms of best practices.

00:27:53.885 --> 00:27:55.510
So I would love to
talk with you if you

00:27:55.510 --> 00:27:59.710
want to be in touch about some
of the other best practices

00:27:59.710 --> 00:28:02.060
that we are identifying
from different companies.

00:28:02.060 --> 00:28:03.830
And I love what you
have at Google--

00:28:03.830 --> 00:28:07.040
Search Inside Yourself-- I
think it's a great program.

00:28:07.040 --> 00:28:09.140
And actually I just
joined the board of Search

00:28:09.140 --> 00:28:10.870
Inside Yourself.

00:28:10.870 --> 00:28:15.240
And I really love all the
work being done there.

00:28:15.240 --> 00:28:16.870
AUDIENCE: Thank you so much.

00:28:16.870 --> 00:28:19.090
One of the things
we started doing

00:28:19.090 --> 00:28:21.340
as a result of reading a
lot of what you share also

00:28:21.340 --> 00:28:24.230
on your blog is no emailing
first thing in the morning,

00:28:24.230 --> 00:28:27.020
and really starting
with strategy,

00:28:27.020 --> 00:28:29.630
or just meditation, or
reflection, as opposed

00:28:29.630 --> 00:28:32.411
to like getting right into that
pulse of the-- fight the email

00:28:32.411 --> 00:28:32.910
urge.

00:28:32.910 --> 00:28:33.630
So thank you.

00:28:33.630 --> 00:28:34.280
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON:
That is fantastic.

00:28:34.280 --> 00:28:35.430
That's major.

00:28:35.430 --> 00:28:37.420
Because again, there's
so much science

00:28:37.420 --> 00:28:42.200
that shows that when you start
your day responding to emails,

00:28:42.200 --> 00:28:46.310
you are basically allowing
other people to hijack your best

00:28:46.310 --> 00:28:51.280
time-- the time when you
can be most creative.

00:28:51.280 --> 00:28:53.670
You're just becoming
reactive and responding

00:28:53.670 --> 00:28:55.865
to what other people
consider their priorities.

00:28:58.940 --> 00:29:01.529
BONITA STEWART: Thanks
for that reminder.

00:29:01.529 --> 00:29:02.070
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:29:02.070 --> 00:29:04.510
My name's Courtney and
I'm interning at Google.

00:29:04.510 --> 00:29:05.870
And this is my first internship.

00:29:05.870 --> 00:29:07.536
And I was wondering
what piece of advice

00:29:07.536 --> 00:29:10.070
you would give yourself
when you were starting out,

00:29:10.070 --> 00:29:12.970
that you wish you had
known looking back.

00:29:12.970 --> 00:29:14.400
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON: Great.

00:29:14.400 --> 00:29:16.285
I would tell myself
to stop worrying.

00:29:20.200 --> 00:29:22.650
Because I was a big worrier.

00:29:22.650 --> 00:29:26.900
I had this voice in my head that
I called the obnoxious roommate

00:29:26.900 --> 00:29:31.630
living in my head
puts me down, that

00:29:31.630 --> 00:29:34.660
has negative fantasies
about the future.

00:29:34.660 --> 00:29:39.850
And I think what I would
have told my young self is,

00:29:39.850 --> 00:29:43.140
be in the moment and recognize.

00:29:43.140 --> 00:29:45.270
One of my favorite
quotes in the book

00:29:45.270 --> 00:29:49.570
is by Rumi, the poet, who said
live life as though everything

00:29:49.570 --> 00:29:51.792
is rigged in your favor.

00:29:51.792 --> 00:29:54.880
You know how often we
tend to live life thinking

00:29:54.880 --> 00:29:57.960
that whatever
happens, immediately

00:29:57.960 --> 00:30:02.820
we'll say just kind of life is
not fair, feeling kind of sorry

00:30:02.820 --> 00:30:04.190
for ourselves.

00:30:04.190 --> 00:30:06.270
And when we look
back at our lives,

00:30:06.270 --> 00:30:10.090
very often some of the
hardest things that happen

00:30:10.090 --> 00:30:12.730
were the things that
opened other doors

00:30:12.730 --> 00:30:15.500
and lead to other
wonderful things happening.

00:30:15.500 --> 00:30:19.390
I mean I have so many stories
like that in my own life.

00:30:19.390 --> 00:30:22.240
And I mention a few
of them in the book

00:30:22.240 --> 00:30:24.970
just to remind all
of us that that's

00:30:24.970 --> 00:30:27.299
the same truth for all of us.

00:30:27.299 --> 00:30:28.132
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:30:31.748 --> 00:30:34.096
AUDIENCE: Hi, my name is Steven.

00:30:34.096 --> 00:30:36.470
You talked a lot about sleep
