vacation time here?

00:39:54.500 --> 00:39:57.180
And this is not kind of
a Google-- sort of like,

00:39:57.180 --> 00:40:01.920
I'm not angling for
anything here at the moment.

00:40:01.920 --> 00:40:05.760
I don't know if anyone
from HR is in the room.

00:40:05.760 --> 00:40:10.450
But really, are we giving
ourselves enough away time?

00:40:10.450 --> 00:40:13.560
And those little moments
that we're taking,

00:40:13.560 --> 00:40:16.520
obviously so important,
walk in Central Park or time

00:40:16.520 --> 00:40:17.330
with a book.

00:40:17.330 --> 00:40:19.580
But how about just
a change of scene?

00:40:19.580 --> 00:40:22.190
Do the Europeans know
something we don't know?

00:40:22.190 --> 00:40:24.560
And do you think that
the winds of change

00:40:24.560 --> 00:40:26.790
are blowing here into
the states eventually?

00:40:26.790 --> 00:40:28.172
Or are we getting enough?

00:40:28.172 --> 00:40:29.630
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON:
Great question.

00:40:29.630 --> 00:40:32.790
And in fact, I wrote a
blog post about it today

00:40:32.790 --> 00:40:34.940
that is on the Huffington Post.

00:40:34.940 --> 00:40:39.100
And the title is Lincoln,
FDR, and the Power

00:40:39.100 --> 00:40:40.800
of a Good Vacation.

00:40:40.800 --> 00:40:50.054
Because FDR, after he was
elected for the third time,

00:40:50.054 --> 00:40:51.470
there was a lot
of pressure on him

00:40:51.470 --> 00:40:55.150
to make a decision on
what would the states do

00:40:55.150 --> 00:40:56.880
regarding the second World War.

00:40:56.880 --> 00:40:59.510
There was a lot of
pressure from Churchill,

00:40:59.510 --> 00:41:03.340
from England for
states to intervene.

00:41:03.340 --> 00:41:06.830
The American public was
completely opposed to it.

00:41:06.830 --> 00:41:10.420
So he had this very big,
difficult decision to make.

00:41:10.420 --> 00:41:11.930
And everybody wanted
him to make it

00:41:11.930 --> 00:41:13.440
right away after the election.

00:41:13.440 --> 00:41:18.880
Instead, he took 10 days off
and went to the Caribbean.

00:41:18.880 --> 00:41:23.000
And during that time, he
came up with what turned out

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:26.540
to be a brilliant idea
of a land lease policy,

00:41:26.540 --> 00:41:29.200
whereby America
would enter the war,

00:41:29.200 --> 00:41:31.770
but basically it
would be a lease

00:41:31.770 --> 00:41:34.290
in terms of the
funding from the UK.

00:41:34.290 --> 00:41:38.640
Anyway, a complicated idea which
the American public bought,

00:41:38.640 --> 00:41:43.560
and allowed America
to enter the war.

00:41:43.560 --> 00:41:47.750
And this would be
really difficult now.

00:41:47.750 --> 00:41:50.710
It would be really
difficult for a president

00:41:50.710 --> 00:41:53.504
to take two days off.

00:41:53.504 --> 00:41:55.170
I mean, you see
immediately, immediately

00:41:55.170 --> 00:41:59.700
it was announced the President
is going to Martha's Vineyard,

00:41:59.700 --> 00:42:02.290
the criticism starts.

00:42:02.290 --> 00:42:07.650
And there is a very
big truth to the need

00:42:07.650 --> 00:42:10.380
for completely
disconnecting, and what

00:42:10.380 --> 00:42:14.060
that does to our health,
our mental clarity,

00:42:14.060 --> 00:42:16.980
our ability to come
up with great ideas.

00:42:16.980 --> 00:42:18.430
And I agree with you.

00:42:18.430 --> 00:42:20.300
I think it's very
important first

00:42:20.300 --> 00:42:24.330
of all, that everybody
takes their full vacation.

00:42:24.330 --> 00:42:29.440
Because Americans are at the
bottom of the list in terms

00:42:29.440 --> 00:42:33.520
of actually taking the
vacation that people are due.

00:42:33.520 --> 00:42:35.050
I don't know what you have here.

00:42:35.050 --> 00:42:38.310
We give three weeks vacation.

00:42:38.310 --> 00:42:41.490
And we tell people
they have to take it.

00:42:41.490 --> 00:42:43.650
And that it's really
important when

00:42:43.650 --> 00:42:46.750
you take a vacation,
to really disconnect.

00:42:46.750 --> 00:42:50.680
And I set an example of a
Christmas when I was away.

00:42:50.680 --> 00:42:53.280
I got together with two
friends-- Mika Brzezinski

00:42:53.280 --> 00:42:54.150
and Cindy Lieber.

00:42:54.150 --> 00:42:56.600
We were in different
parts vacationing.

00:42:56.600 --> 00:42:58.980
But we all agreed to
do a digital detox

00:42:58.980 --> 00:43:04.360
for a week, where I checked
in with the office just twice

00:43:04.360 --> 00:43:05.000
a day.

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:09.430
And other than that, I
was completely off email.

00:43:09.430 --> 00:43:11.730
So whatever you
need to do to have

00:43:11.730 --> 00:43:14.160
as much complete
disconnection as possible,

00:43:14.160 --> 00:43:18.030
because 56% of people return
from vacation more exhausted

00:43:18.030 --> 00:43:20.610
than before.

00:43:20.610 --> 00:43:22.670
Because they tried
to be on vacation,

00:43:22.670 --> 00:43:26.840
be with their families, and
stay connected to their office.

00:43:26.840 --> 00:43:30.510
So absolutely, we need
to rethink vacations

00:43:30.510 --> 00:43:37.450
and how important they are to
the way we function in our work

00:43:37.450 --> 00:43:39.415
as well as in our lives.

00:43:39.415 --> 00:43:42.410
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:43:42.410 --> 00:43:44.170
AUDIENCE: Hi, Arianna.

00:43:44.170 --> 00:43:45.460
My name is Jason Vee.

00:43:45.460 --> 00:43:49.220
I work under Bonita's org in
the entertainment and music

00:43:49.220 --> 00:43:51.360
partnerships team.

00:43:51.360 --> 00:43:54.720
My question to you
is about gender.

00:43:54.720 --> 00:43:59.210
In terms of the tips that
you've outlined for thriving,

00:43:59.210 --> 00:44:01.630
do you think that there are
any fundamental differences

00:44:01.630 --> 00:44:08.110
or tweaks for a man
looking at leaning back

00:44:08.110 --> 00:44:10.830
to be able to lean in further
and become successful,

00:44:10.830 --> 00:44:12.799
or are all these
concepts that you're

00:44:12.799 --> 00:44:14.590
talking about from a
scientific perspective

00:44:14.590 --> 00:44:17.580
and your own perspectives,
complete gender neutral?

00:44:17.580 --> 00:44:20.000
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON:
Completely gender neutral.

00:44:20.000 --> 00:44:21.970
Absolutely no difference.

00:44:21.970 --> 00:44:27.560
I think men and women need this.

00:44:27.560 --> 00:44:30.600
I mean every sex needs
them as much as the other.

00:44:30.600 --> 00:44:31.660
How many sexes are there?

00:44:31.660 --> 00:44:34.570
Only two.

00:44:34.570 --> 00:44:36.290
It doesn't matter
what sex you are.

00:44:36.290 --> 00:44:40.550
The problem is that sleep
deprivation and burnout

00:44:40.550 --> 00:44:44.800
have become a kind of
macho badge of honor.

00:44:44.800 --> 00:44:47.000
So sometimes men
have a harder time

00:44:47.000 --> 00:44:50.180
incorporating these new ideas.

00:44:50.180 --> 00:44:52.960
But if any man has a
hard time incorporating,

00:44:52.960 --> 00:44:55.040
they should look at athletes.

00:44:55.040 --> 00:45:00.970
They should look at what
LeBron James or Richard Sherman

00:45:00.970 --> 00:45:05.090
from the Seattle Seahawks are
doing around sleep, meditation,

00:45:05.090 --> 00:45:08.320
and all these things, and how
they actually consider them

00:45:08.320 --> 00:45:10.630
performance enhancement tools.

00:45:10.630 --> 00:45:14.300
And just one of the
image for the men who

00:45:14.300 --> 00:45:21.500
have a harder time disconnecting
and allowing themselves to have

00:45:21.500 --> 00:45:27.910
time for renewal, is to watch an
interview that Charlie Rose did

00:45:27.910 --> 00:45:30.830
with Andy Murray, you
know, the tennis player.

00:45:30.830 --> 00:45:33.310
And Andy Murray was
talking about how

00:45:33.310 --> 00:45:37.070
when he's fully
recharged and rested,

00:45:37.070 --> 00:45:41.510
the ball is coming at
him in slow motion.

00:45:41.510 --> 00:45:44.930
So he's in a place where
he can deal with it,

00:45:44.930 --> 00:45:48.010
and have the clarity of
thought to make a decision,

00:45:48.010 --> 00:45:50.670
because it's not coming
at him like that.

00:45:50.670 --> 00:45:52.850
And I think it's a great
metaphor, because I

00:45:52.850 --> 00:45:54.740
know when I'm
exhausted, everything

00:45:54.740 --> 00:45:59.100
is coming at me all at
once, and it's overwhelming.

00:45:59.100 --> 00:46:01.070
And I get reactive.

00:46:01.070 --> 00:46:06.520
And I'm not as able to
operate from my best, kind

00:46:06.520 --> 00:46:08.818
of wiser self.

00:46:08.818 --> 00:46:11.500
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:46:11.500 --> 00:46:12.680
AUDIENCE: Hi, I'm Jenna.

00:46:12.680 --> 00:46:14.263
I've been with Google
for three years,

00:46:14.263 --> 00:46:15.877
based in our Singapore office.

00:46:15.877 --> 00:46:18.210
And I've been tasked with
running around countries where

00:46:18.210 --> 00:46:19.876
we don't have offices
in Southeast Asia,

00:46:19.876 --> 00:46:21.460
to figure out what
to do for Google.

00:46:21.460 --> 00:46:23.840
So I spent most of my time
in Pakistan, Sri Lanka,

00:46:23.840 --> 00:46:25.490
and Bangladesh.

00:46:25.490 --> 00:46:27.850
These are some of the
most highly repressive,

00:46:27.850 --> 00:46:30.000
volatile, corrupt
countries in the world.

00:46:30.000 --> 00:46:32.440
I recently moved back to
join Jared Cohen's team.

00:46:32.440 --> 00:46:33.940
You mentioned the
Google Ideas team.

00:46:33.940 --> 00:46:35.481
So I'm still operating
in that space.

00:46:35.481 --> 00:46:38.270
But I'm experiencing some
reverse culture shock.

00:46:38.270 --> 00:46:40.640
We're noticing as I watch
the news, how frequently we

00:46:40.640 --> 00:46:43.650
complain about first world
problems-- quote, unquote--

00:46:43.650 --> 00:46:46.510
and how we can get overly
consumed with these issues

00:46:46.510 --> 00:46:47.640
that only we face.

00:46:47.640 --> 00:46:49.920
Be it in New York or
in the United States.

00:46:49.920 --> 00:46:53.790
And I'm wondering in your life,
as you've grown and developed

00:46:53.790 --> 00:46:56.120
your wisdom and kept
yourself grounded, how do you

00:46:56.120 --> 00:46:58.830
maintain this perspective?

00:46:58.830 --> 00:47:00.830
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON: Well
maintaining perspective

00:47:00.830 --> 00:47:05.990
is actually one of the best ways
to connect to our own wisdom.

00:47:05.990 --> 00:47:10.250
And looking at what's happening
in the rest of the world

00:47:10.250 --> 00:47:13.880
is a great way to
maintain perspective.

00:47:13.880 --> 00:47:18.370
In the same way we talked
about death recently,

00:47:18.370 --> 00:47:21.530
Socrates said
practice death daily.

00:47:21.530 --> 00:47:23.910
He didn't mean it
in a morbid sense,

00:47:23.910 --> 00:47:26.520
but he meant it in
the sense that when

00:47:26.520 --> 00:47:29.520
we remember that
death is part of life.

00:47:29.520 --> 00:47:31.910
And when you go to
Pakistan or Sri Lanka,

00:47:31.910 --> 00:47:38.610
and you see that death is much
more present in everyday life,

00:47:38.610 --> 00:47:41.210
because of the
level of violence,

00:47:41.210 --> 00:47:45.530
because of the level
of poverty, again, it

00:47:45.530 --> 00:47:47.650
does put everything
in perspective.

00:47:47.650 --> 00:47:53.490
And I think the amount
of worry that we

00:47:53.490 --> 00:47:59.390
bring to everyday issues that
don't deserve worry diminishes

00:47:59.390 --> 00:48:01.510
when we have that
kind of perspective.

00:48:01.510 --> 00:48:03.440
Let me just say one
other thing, which

00:48:03.440 --> 00:48:08.150
is that everything we discussed
today, and everything in Thrive

00:48:08.150 --> 00:48:12.620
applies just as much to
people in extreme adversity.

00:48:12.620 --> 00:48:16.680
Because in fact, the more
adverse the circumstance

00:48:16.680 --> 00:48:21.980
of your life, the more you need
to tap into your own resilience

00:48:21.980 --> 00:48:26.120
to be able to survive,
and even thrive,

00:48:26.120 --> 00:48:28.110
and transcend your
circumstances.

00:48:28.110 --> 00:48:30.310
That's why in the
book I even include

00:48:30.310 --> 00:48:33.850
examples of people in
concentration camps.

00:48:33.850 --> 00:48:36.050
Because there are
people who are able to

00:48:36.050 --> 00:48:40.850
transcend even the most
horrific circumstances.

00:48:40.850 --> 00:48:48.360
And there are others who fall
apart when they lose a job.

00:48:48.360 --> 00:48:50.470
In fact, there is a
very interesting study

00:48:50.470 --> 00:48:53.320
in the book by the
University of Chicago,

00:48:53.320 --> 00:49:01.050
that tracked what happened
to thousands of people who

00:49:01.050 --> 00:49:04.390
were fired by the
Illinois Bell Company.

00:49:04.390 --> 00:49:08.140
One of the biggest corporate
downsizings in history.

00:49:08.140 --> 00:49:14.210
And they followed them,
and 2/3 of them fell apart.

00:49:14.210 --> 00:49:19.390
They became alcoholics,
they became depressed.

00:49:19.390 --> 00:49:23.100
And 1/3 thrived and
went on to bigger jobs,

00:49:23.100 --> 00:49:24.510
started their own company.

00:49:24.510 --> 00:49:32.470
So the same thing has a very
dramatically different impact

00:49:32.470 --> 00:49:35.640
on different people depending
on how resilient and connected

00:49:35.640 --> 00:49:38.620
with their own inner
strength and wisdom they are.

00:49:38.620 --> 00:49:39.819
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:49:39.819 --> 00:49:42.110
BONITA STEWART: I think this
