00:53:23.272 --> 00:53:24.980
ARIANNA HUFFINGTON:
Great final question.

00:53:24.980 --> 00:53:27.646
First of all, let me
just say that the way we

00:53:27.646 --> 00:53:30.810
are living and working is crazy.

00:53:30.810 --> 00:53:32.530
So there's no
question about that.

00:53:32.530 --> 00:53:34.750
It's like, I think
that as we are now

00:53:34.750 --> 00:53:37.920
in a period of
transition, which I think

00:53:37.920 --> 00:53:40.240
is going to be as
big when we look back

00:53:40.240 --> 00:53:44.300
as moving from the Middle
Ages to the Renaissance.

00:53:44.300 --> 00:53:46.490
In the Middle Ages,
remember, people actually

00:53:46.490 --> 00:53:51.630
did believe that the whole
world revolved around the Earth.

00:53:51.630 --> 00:53:52.880
And they really believed that.

00:53:52.880 --> 00:53:55.450
Now if somebody's
a flat-Earther,

00:53:55.450 --> 00:53:58.850
we don't think very
highly of them, right?

00:53:58.850 --> 00:54:01.430
So I think there
will come a day--

00:54:01.430 --> 00:54:06.280
I hope soon-- when actually
the collective delusion

00:54:06.280 --> 00:54:08.540
that burnout is the
only way to succeed

00:54:08.540 --> 00:54:15.000
will be seen as completely
barbaric and completely also

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:17.700
unscientific.

00:54:17.700 --> 00:54:20.960
But right now, we
see everything.

00:54:20.960 --> 00:54:24.110
We see the resistance
that you're talking about.

00:54:24.110 --> 00:54:28.869
And we see early
adopters changing

00:54:28.869 --> 00:54:30.910
the way they are living,
not just for themselves,

00:54:30.910 --> 00:54:33.600
but for their teams,
or their companies.

00:54:33.600 --> 00:54:35.920
So we are living in this
period of transition,

00:54:35.920 --> 00:54:39.612
where the reason for my
really wanting to be here,

00:54:39.612 --> 00:54:41.820
wanting to be speaking and
writing about these things

00:54:41.820 --> 00:54:45.580
that I believe we can accelerate
the transition by sharing

00:54:45.580 --> 00:54:47.970
our stories, and
by making people

00:54:47.970 --> 00:54:50.570
realize that it's not laziness.

00:54:50.570 --> 00:54:52.180
On the contrary,
the people who are

00:54:52.180 --> 00:54:54.305
going to be the most
creative, the people who

00:54:54.305 --> 00:54:57.500
are going to bring about
the most fundamental changes

00:54:57.500 --> 00:55:02.340
are people who learn to
disconnect, and reconnect

00:55:02.340 --> 00:55:04.770
with themselves, their
wisdom, and strength.

00:55:04.770 --> 00:55:09.190
And so we need new role models.

00:55:09.190 --> 00:55:11.320
That's why for
example, I always talk

00:55:11.320 --> 00:55:15.689
about people who are
successful, running big teams,

00:55:15.689 --> 00:55:16.730
but doing it differently.

00:55:16.730 --> 00:55:18.840
And let me just
mention one of them.

00:55:18.840 --> 00:55:20.530
Padmasree Warrior.

00:55:20.530 --> 00:55:23.500
She's the chief technology
officer of Cisco.

00:55:23.500 --> 00:55:26.930
She oversees tens of
thousands of engineers.

00:55:26.930 --> 00:55:29.790
We had her speak at
our Thrive conference.

00:55:29.790 --> 00:55:32.680
And she said, "I
sleep for eight hours.

00:55:32.680 --> 00:55:34.430
I meditate every day.

00:55:34.430 --> 00:55:35.630
I paint.

00:55:35.630 --> 00:55:37.130
I do haiku.

00:55:37.130 --> 00:55:40.770
And every Saturday I
do a digital detox."

00:55:40.770 --> 00:55:42.270
And it was amazing.

00:55:42.270 --> 00:55:43.970
She's an engineer.

00:55:43.970 --> 00:55:47.320
She's not lazy.

00:55:47.320 --> 00:55:49.370
She's super successful.

00:55:49.370 --> 00:55:52.140
And she's doing it
a different way.

00:55:52.140 --> 00:55:55.600
So I think especially for
all the young people here,

00:55:55.600 --> 00:55:59.380
those still in college, we need
to publicize these role models.

00:55:59.380 --> 00:56:01.620
I've been talking about
her so much on my book

00:56:01.620 --> 00:56:03.060
tour, that she
emailed me and said

00:56:03.060 --> 00:56:05.550
Random House wants
her to do a book.

00:56:05.550 --> 00:56:06.430
I said, great.

00:56:06.430 --> 00:56:08.200
That's really what we need.

00:56:08.200 --> 00:56:12.130
We need more and more people
to hear that there are new ways

00:56:12.130 --> 00:56:15.170
to accomplish, to
achieve, to excel

00:56:15.170 --> 00:56:18.560
without burnout, and
without sacrificing

00:56:18.560 --> 00:56:22.110
your health, your
relationships, and your life.

00:56:22.110 --> 00:56:22.910
Thank you so much.

00:56:22.910 --> 00:56:24.480
BONITA STEWART: Thank you.

00:56:24.480 --> 00:56:27.530
[APPLAUSE]

